---
import ProjectLayout from '../../layouts/ProjectLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---
<ProjectLayout
  title="Who Pays to Park? Mapping Tel Aviv's Parking Equity by Neighborhood"
  year="2023"
  category="Urban Policy Analysis · Cartography"
  tools={['Python', 'GeoPandas', 'QGIS', 'Choropleth Mapping', 'Spatial Join']}
>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Background</h2>
    <div class="proj-body">
      <p>
        Tel Aviv's curbside parking splits into paid (blue-and-white), free (white-line) and grey
        regulated zones — and its rollout is politically sensitive, since who pays tracks closely
        with neighborhood demographics. This project mapped that distribution to answer one
        question: is the burden of paid parking falling evenly across the city?
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Maps — Parking Type by Neighborhood</h2>
    <img
      src={`${base}/maps/parking-blue-white.png`}
      alt="Choropleth map showing percentage of blue-and-white paid parking by Tel Aviv neighborhood"
      class="proj-map"
      loading="lazy"
    />
    <p class="proj-map-caption">
      Share of blue-and-white (paid) parking spaces by neighborhood. Darker shading indicates higher
      proportion of paid curbside.
    </p>
    <img
      src={`${base}/maps/parking-free-neighborhood.png`}
      alt="Choropleth map showing percentage of free parking by Tel Aviv neighborhood"
      class="proj-map"
      loading="lazy"
    />
    <p class="proj-map-caption">
      Share of free (unpaid) parking by neighborhood — the inverse of the paid parking distribution,
      highlighting which areas retain the most free curbside access.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Methodology</h2>
    <ul class="proj-list">
      <li>Spatially joined the municipal parking inventory to neighborhood boundaries with <strong>GeoPandas</strong>, computing the share of paid vs. free spaces per area.</li>
      <li>Built <strong>choropleth maps</strong> in <strong>QGIS</strong> — <strong>Jenks natural-breaks</strong> for technical review, simplified manual breaks for committee presentations.</li>
      <li>Tested color palettes for perceptual clarity and color-vision-deficiency accessibility.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Results</h2>
    <div class="proj-body">
      <p>
        The pattern was stark: central neighborhoods are overwhelmingly paid, while peripheral areas
        retain large shares of free curbside. That portrait now informs committee discussions on
        the pace and geography of the next rollout phase.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

</ProjectLayout>

<style>
  :global(.proj-list) {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 10px;
    max-width: 68ch;
  }
  :global(.proj-list li) {
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: #2A2A2A;
    padding-left: 1.2em;
    position: relative;
  }
  :global(.proj-list li::before) {
    content: '—';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: #3D5E35;
    font-weight: 600;
  }
</style>
